**The thesis:** everyone sees the one child star who made it out clean. The Type 3 lens flips it: the put-togetherness didn't survive the child stardom, it *was* the child stardom. Her family moved states on a six-year-old's begging, so flawless delivery became how a small girl kept everyone okay. Key evidence in her own words: "I am kind of trying to untether from my own perfectionism," "I'm starving for the work," and her advice to her ten-year-old self: "you don't have to be perfect... You're safe."

**Structural highlights:** the hook is the locker she couldn't open at fifteen; the bespoke section braids Sally Draper's milestones against Kiernan's (Sally got her period first, scripted); the empathy turn rebuilds the "stilted/poised" criticism from her own wound-vocabulary ("wall on wall on wall"); the ending is her mother applauding her mistakes. Two sourced stats: Mad Men's four straight Outstanding Drama Emmys (2008–2011) and Forbes 30 Under 30 (2025).

